en, decided the Labor Board, were also entitled to collect I Slabaugh, Miss Martha Coy and Hugh McGrananhan, all of Alliance. Miss\nfor the pay they lost.\nHarsha is the youngest daughter of Mr. and Mrs. J. Porter Donaldson of\nThis is the first time since the Wagner Act was passed ten years ago I Sebring, and until recently has been employed in the offices of the Sebring\nthat an employer has been stuck for pay lost by workers against whom the I Pottery Company.\nemployer did not personally discriminate. Chester Green and William Myler, dishmakers at plant No. 5 of the\nThis, however, does not mean that the decisions on the point, up to now, I Homer Laughlin China Conjpany, has issued a challenge to all crib players\nwere the other way. The fact of the matter, peculiar as it may seem, is that I this district.\nthere simply were no decisions on the subject at all. I An interesting dance was enjoyed on two occasions last week, when folks\nenNuiMwi.wri.\u2019u from the Warehouse and Decorating shops of plants Nos. 4 and 5 of the\nLI A Bl LU Y FOR CONSEQUENCES I Homer Laughlin China Company staged a dinner hour dance in the shop.\nNow this decnsion may, to some people appear a bit unfair.\nAnd we may I They had an orchestra which wos composed of pottery lads, Paul Miller Bill\nbe sure that employer representatives will beef about it. Why, it will be I Adams, and Seth Smith.\nargued, should an employer be required to pay people when there is no work I Services for Arthur Carlton, Jr., well-known potter who died on a\nfor them\nWell, let\u2019s see about that. Why wasn\u2019t there work for them? In this case I home of his father-in-law, Thomas Wright, in Trenton, N. J. Bearers were\nthese four employes were out of work only because the boss had unlawfully I John Hibbs, Thomas Dennis, Arnold and William Foster, James Cartlidge\nfired the striking piolders.\nland John Ellis.\nThe four men had broken no law. It wasn\u2019t their fault that there was I Mr. and Mrs. William H. Kelly of Trenton, announce the birth of a baby\nno work. The boss, on the contrary, had broken the law, and his unlawful I girl at St. Francis Hospital on last Saturday. Mr. Kelly is associated with\nrefusal to reinstate the strikers (their jobs had not been filled) was the I the Thomas Maddock Sons Pottery Company.\ndirect reason for the lack of work. I Edward J. Black, Sr., of Trenton. N. J., who was employed as a sanitary\nTherei s an old legal principle which goes something like this: Where I presser, previous to his retirement several years ago, died on Thanksgiving\none of two innocent persons must suffer, he who has caused the loss should Day at his home following a week\u2019s illness,\nbe the one to bear it. If this is true, then it must be all the more so where\nthe one who bear? the. loss is not innocent but guilty.\nIn short, the Rockwood case in effect decides that when an employer\nbreaks the law he is responsible for the national consequences. That\u2019s only\nfair and right and as it should be.\nWRINKLF I Corporations made huge profits out of the war, but did not risk a nickel\nito be|p uncle Sam win. On the contrary, during the war years corporations\nThere\u2019s one wrinkle in all this, however, which should be pointed out. I reduced their total \u201cplant and equipment investment\u201d by $3,600,000,000.\nYou\u2019employer\nll notice that we have emphasized the fact that in the Rockwood case mi,... i... i i\nthe had acted unlawfully. This unlawful conduct consisted in th lhat st\u00bbrtl'\"K \u00a3act 18 revealed by a Federal Iteserve \u201cBulletm.\u201d\nfact that he had fired the strikers for striking. If, on the other hand, he I It shows that, when the Japs hit Pearl Harbor in December, 1941, a.\nhadn\u2019t fired them, the four men would have been out of luck despite the I corporations in the United States, except banks and insurance companies,\nfa that they were out of work. I had $100,300,060,(MM) invested in plant and equipment.\n\u00a3a8\u201c here\u2019 80 ev\u00a7fy\u00b0ne I By March, 1945, when the war was almost over, they had reduced their\n1 investments to $96,700,000,000.\na wewvou\nQUESTIONS AM) ANSWERS |tbe war but it was paid for by the government, the \u201cBulletin\u201d explains. In\nQuestion: With the War Labor Board going out, will the National Labor lother words, Uncle Sam took all the risks.\nRelations Board resume having complete charge of all labor relations? I\nS i- i I Now war is over, nut the country faces another great\nemergenev\u2014safety\u2018\u2018\nAnswer: The NLRB never had full jurisdiction over labor relations. Its lpeacetimethe\nunemployment. Will the corporations continue to play\nunsdiction is strictly limited to enforcing the Wagner act. You have over- fir8t\u201e? Or will they invest billions of dollars in new plants and equipment\nlooked the Department of Labor, including the Conciliation Service, and (and thus help provide johs for millions of men\u2019\nseveral small groups attached to other government agencies.\n____J\nkt^STi^ refcrenc\u201c10 *ppropri,\u2018u unil' Unemployment Insurance Informatjon\nAnswer: Too many people confuse unit and union. The appropriate bar-1 ___________\ngaining unit is that group of workers which, because of various circumstances, n if\nthe NLRB feels will be most effective fbr bargaining purposes. In the major-1 9\u2019 unemSnvid Urinsurance, thgn find a job4,\nity of cases it will consist of what is known a& a unit of production workers, onIy to become unefnployed again, what d9 I do\nor production and maintenance workers. Sometimes the unit will consist of I A.-*-Contact the nearest United States Employment Service office bring\nmembers of a certain craft. At other times the various workers, including thelyour work application up to date, and file a continued (or additional)\u2019claim\ncrafts, will be joined in one industrial unit. Various considerations are taken I This time you will not have to serve a waiting period as you did when you\ninto account in fixing the unit. Among them art bargaining history, similar-1 filed youi* original claim. You Will\n-\u2014benefits\nI James Fansh, a former local kilnhand, who has been critically ill for the\nI gjx years asro and had not been able to do any kiln work since*\nIbenville, Ohio, was married on Thanksgiving day.\nI Vice President Frank Hull and Will T. Blake, tditor of the Potters Herald.\nI Wheeling potters will stage banquet and get-together on December 7.\nI The affair will be held in honor of the new members being transferred over to\nI Local No. 6 from Local 28.\nI In the neighborhood of 100 wholesalers and distributors of plumbing\n(supplies from various sections of the country, inspected the sanitary plant of\nNO WORK lthp Thomas Maddock\u2019s Sons Co. in Trenton, N. J., last week. Special enter-\nI motored to Columbus.\nThursday, November 29, 1945\nFrom The Herald Files\nTHIRTY-FIVE YEARS AGO\nI The Turners and Handlers\u2019 Local No. 10 will elect officers at their meet\ns'*. ling on next Monday evening. The auditing committee composed of brothers\nV? I John McNicol, James Gibson and George Wetzel will make their report\n\u25a0\u00bbt I at this meeting.\nfeatures were provided by Harold S. Maddock, vice president of the\nI Calvin Coolidge attend the second annual reunion of the employees of the\nwere marrjed jn Sebring last week. The attendants were Mr. and Mrs. Howard\nI train near Callup, New Mexico, were held last Thursday afternoon from the\nBig Business\" Didn't Risk a Cent\nI There was a great expansion of factories and production machinery during\nreceive\ni\nBlake was a visitor at Local Union 10\u2019s meeting and by\nremarks on the progress of the free night school which\nTWENTY YEARS AGO\nThe Ohio Ceramic Industries Association, of which Thomas B. Anderson\nof the Pope-Gosser China Company, Coshocton, is president, and Keith Mc\n.Afee of Cambridge, Ohio, is secretary, held its first annual meeting at Colum-\n7\